{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15977"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15977"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.2,0.65,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75243"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8668"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60751"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3618"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8595"},{"type":"tags","id":"10625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75243"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents after a positive home pregnancy test. She is interested in understanding early pregnancy development. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring implantation, one layer of cells is primarily responsible for producing human chorionic gonadotropin, eroding maternal blood vessels, and facilitating nutrient exchange between mother and embryo while keeping the two separate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is primarily responsible for these functions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epithelium of the uterine mucosa","Hypoblast","Cytotrophoblast","Syncytiotrophoblast","Epiblast"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early pregnancy, the blastocyst implants into the maternal endometrium through a complex process involving multiple cell layers. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyncytiotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E is the outer layer of the trophoblast that forms through the fusion of underlying cytotrophoblast cells. It forms the outermost layer of the placenta. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esyncytiotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E produces human chorionic gonadotropin, which maintains the corpus luteum and therefore the pregnancy. It also contains enzymes that digest maternal tissue during implantation and forms the interface for nutrient and gas exchange between maternal and foetal circulation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E consists of individual stem cells that fuse to form the syncytiotrophoblast. It does not directly perform the functions mentioned in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepithelium of the uterine mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E is the maternal tissue that the blastocyst initially contacts during implantation. However, it does not produce pregnancy hormones or facilitate nutrient exchange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoblast\u003C/strong\u003E (primitive endoderm) and \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiblast\u003C/strong\u003E are components of the inner cell mass that give rise to embryonic and extraembryonic tissues, but neither is involved in the immediate implantation process or hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The syncytiotrophoblast is the outer multinucleated layer of the trophoblast that invades the maternal endometrium during implantation.","The syncytiotrophoblast produces human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), which maintains the corpus luteum during early pregnancy.","The syncytiotrophoblast forms the maternal-fetal interface and is crucial for nutrient exchange and hormone production."],"references":["Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Renaud SJ, Jeyarajah MJ. How trophoblasts fuse: an in-depth look into placental syncytiotrophoblast formation. Cell Mol Life Sci. 2022;79(8):433. Published 2022 Jul 20. doi:10.1007/s00018-022-04475-z"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60751"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15977"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60751"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T14:01:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T14:02:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8668"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75243"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"met